	<title><a href="https://nordicapis.com/">Nordic APIs</a> LiveCast</title>
	<presentation id="index">
		<title>A Product Perspective on API Lifecycle Management</title>
		<toc class="abstract">A lot is being written about API products and how API management should become less focused on pure technology and more on a product perspective for APIs. Is that true for all APIs? And if not, how do you decide how to manage a specific API? In this session, we'll look at how to determine which APIs can benefit most when being managed as products and how API lifecycle management changes when you take a product perspective.</toc>
		<author><a href="http://dret.net/netdret/">Erik Wilde</a> <a href="http://twitter.com/dret" class="twitter-follow-button" data-size="large" title="Erik Wilde on Twitter: @dret">(<code>@dret</code>)</a></author>
		<date short="2023-01-18">January 18, 2023</date>
		<copyright>2023 Erik Wilde</copyright>
		<slide id="summary">
			<title>Summary</title>
			<p class="abstract"><toc class="abstract"/></p>
		</slide>
		<part id="business-vision">
			<title>Based on Business Vision</title>
			<slide id="integration-composability">
				<title>Integration vs. Composability</title>
				<ul>
					<li>APIs can be used for 1:1 interconnections</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Componentization often is one of the goals of modern <em>software architecture</em></li>
						<li>All communication between components is <q>API</q> based</li>
						<li>Connecting components for a single purpose is using a <em>project mindset</em></li>
					</ul>
					<li>APIs can be used for 1:n interconnections</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Changeability and flexibility are goals of modern <em>business architecture</em></li>
						<li>Value chains must adapt to changing needs and new competition</li>
						<li>Designing components for reuse is using a <em>product mindset</em></li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="spice-girls-question">
				<title>Nobody (really) wants APIs</title>
				<img title="Tell me what you really really want" src="spice-girls-really-really-want.jpg" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v0z_6pXeimw" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
			</slide>
		</part>
		<part id="product-mindset">
			<title>Product Mindset</title>
			<slide id="product-definition">
				<title>What is a Product?</title>
				<img href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/product" title="Merriam Webster: Product" src="product-merriam-webster.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="good-api">
				<title>What is a Good API (Product)?</title>
				<img src="coffee-capsules.png" title="Coffee Capsules" style=" float: right ; height : 65% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; "/>
				<ol>
					<li>It's well-designed</li>
					<li>It's designed with consumers in mind</li>
					<li>It's designed to be used by many consumers</li>
					<li>It's following a product lifecycle</li>
					<li>It's easily findable and consumable</li>
					<li>It's marketed with the target audience in mind</li>
				</ol>
			</slide>
			<slide id="dx-overrated-dx">
				<title>All You Need is DX?</title>
				<img title="Developer Experience" src="developer-experience-dx.png" class="fullsize" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="dx-overrated-ux">
				<title>What's in it for the Users?</title>
				<img title="User Experience" src="developer-experience-ux.png" class="fullsize" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="dx-overrated-vx">
				<title>What's in it for the Organization?</title>
				<img title="Value Exchange" src="developer-experience-vx.png" class="fullsize" />
			</slide>
		</part>
		<part id="consumption">
			<title>Focus on API Consumption</title>
			<slide id="product-vs-solution">
				<title>Products Need Marketing</title>
				<ul>
					<li><q>Traditional 1:1 integration</q> creates one solution for each problem</li>
					<li><q>API 1:n composability</q> creates a product intended for a market</li>
					<li>Products drive value <em>only when they are being consumed</em></li>
					<li>The main drivers for your business are excellent API product candidates</li>
					<ul>
						<li><em>Ordering</em> should be open so that partners or 3rd party apps can create orders</li>
						<li><em>Delivery</em> should be flexible so that new delivery options are easy to add</li>
						<li><em>Invoicing</em> should be flexible so that new payment methods are easy to add</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="marketing-definition">
				<title>What is Marketing?</title>
				<img href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/marketing" title="Merriam Webster: Marketing" src="marketing-merriam-webster.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-marketplace">
				<title>What is an API Marketplace?</title>
				<img href="https://developer.commerzbank.com/products/api-catalog" title="Commerzbank Developer Portal: API Catalog" src="commerzbank-api-catalog.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-marketplace-architecture">
				<title>Building an API Marketplace</title>
				<img title="API Marketplace Architecture" src="API-management.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
			</slide>
		</part>
		<part id="conclusions">
			<slide id="product-management">
				<title>API Product Management</title>
				<ol>
					<li>Focus on APIs well-aligned with business strategy and goals</li>
					<li>Design APIs as products with a lifecycle in mind</li>
					<li>Invest in marketing to get most out of your products</li>
				</ol>
			</slide>
